Yellow Metal, Gray Reputation

The scandal over gold quality at America's Fort Knox logically continues the story of France's "golden evacuation" from the US: it turns out that a significant portion of American bullion technically fails to meet modern standards, and major central banks are already voting with their feet and their money.

What are the claims about?

Analysts at Money Metals, drawing on open materials from the US Treasury and inventory documents from the early 2010s, point out: only around 17% of the bullion listed in American treasury reserves has a purity of 995 or higher — that is, meets modern exchange standards for "pure" gold suitable for quick trading and delivery to major platforms like LBMA. The rest consists of old, low-purity bullion.

According to the inventories discussed in specialized materials, the average purity of the entire volume is around 916 (that is, 91.6% gold in the metal). This is the classic "coin" or "semi-finished" format, which looked fine in the mid-20th century, but does not meet the requirements for deliverable gold in the 21st century. To turn this reserve into a full-fledged exchange asset, it needs to be massively remelted and further refined — with expenditures of time and money.

A separate problem is the absence of a modern comprehensive audit. An independent review of deep storage reserves has not been conducted since the 1950s: after the closure of the "gold window," only internal checks and demonstration tours for journalists were carried out, as in 1974, when a delegation was shown through one section of the vault without systematic verification of bullion against registers or purity checks.

For critics, this is the main argument: the world relies on figures that no one has truly confirmed for decades.

Against this backdrop, the decision by the Bank of France became an example of how a major player can simultaneously solve both a technical and political problem. Asset owners did not "sell off gold," but rather got rid of precisely the old and non-standard bullion that remained overseas.

These 129 tons were sold at peak prices, and with the proceeds, an equal amount of already modern, highly liquid gold was purchased, which was physically placed in Paris. The volume of reserves remained the same, but its quality and jurisdiction changed.

The French case demonstrated to fellow club members a very simple algorithm: there is no need to argue with Washington about the contents of the vault — questionable gold can be sold to those who don't ask extra questions (and even make a decent profit on volatility), and with that money buy normal metal and store it at home.
